# Cyber Kill Chain

![Cyber Kill Chain](cyber_kill_chain.png)

The ransomware incident followed a structured Cyber Kill Chain attack lifecycle demonstrating how attackers progressed from initial access to enterprise-wide disruption.

### Attack Stages Covered

| Stage | Description |
|---|---|
| Reconnaissance | Attackers gathered organizational and employee-related information to identify potential targets and vulnerabilities. |
| Phishing | A phishing email was used as the initial access vector to compromise enterprise endpoints. |
| Malware Execution | Malicious scripts and unauthorized processes were executed within compromised systems. |
| Privilege Escalation | Attackers attempted to gain elevated access to critical enterprise resources and administrative privileges. |
| Lateral Movement | Unauthorized movement across interconnected systems enabled broader infrastructure compromise. |
| Ransomware Deployment | Enterprise systems and files were encrypted, disrupting operational continuity and business services. |
| Recovery | Incident response and recovery operations were initiated to restore affected systems and improve resilience. |

### Key Security Observations

- Increased phishing exposure risk
- Weak privileged access management
- Elevated ransomware propagation capability
- Operational dependency on interconnected systems
- Importance of continuous security monitoring
- Need for improved incident response readiness

The Cyber Kill Chain analysis provided better visibility into attacker behavior, enterprise security gaps, and business risks associated with modern ransomware threats.
